<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Chiroderma gorgasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically very similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. trinitatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="trinitatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">C. trinitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both species have a small cranial and body size for the genus (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Cranial and body measurements of six taxa of the big-eyed bat Chiroderma. See Material and methods for variable abbreviations." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/552402E697D21C976F1B82B8AEA92335" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableUuid="552402E697D21C976F1B82B8AEA92335">2</tableCitation>
, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Principal Component Analysis (PCA) carried out using the correlation matrix of ten measurements for six taxa of the big-eyed bat Chiroderma. C. trinitatum gorgasi (■) C. trinitatum trinitatum (□), C. salvini (x), C. villosum (+), C. doriae (●), and C. improvisum (◊)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.918.48786.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/388741" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">4</figureCitation>
), an undeveloped sagittal and lambdoidal crest, a rounded occipital complex, a short nasal aperture, and undeveloped supraorbital region. However, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. trinitatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="trinitatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">C. trinitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a third posterior cusp on the second lower premolar, which is absent in 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. gorgasi" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="gorgasi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">C. gorgasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Lateral view of the second lower premolar on the right mandible of A Chiroderma gorgasi and B C. trinitatum. The arrow points to the accessory cusp that is absent in C. gorgasi and present in C. trinitatum. But note the variation in cusp formation in C. trinitatum." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.918.48786.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/388742" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">5</figureCitation>
). This cusp in 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. trinitatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="trinitatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">C. trinitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may vary from very pointed and developed to rounded and less marked, but is always present. In addition, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. gorgasi" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="gorgasi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">C. gorgasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tends to have a broader braincase (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 4" captionStartId="T4" captionText="Table 4. ANOVA comparing Chiroderma trinitatum trinitatum to C. doriae, C. improvisum, C. villosum, C. salvini, and C. trinitatum gorgasi. * indicates significantly distinct variables (p ≤ 5 %)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5DE7E2B1F6DB1E28895E50CE44194204" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableUuid="5DE7E2B1F6DB1E28895E50CE44194204">4</tableCitation>
) and a flatter supraorbital region, which tends to be deeper in 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. trinitatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="trinitatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">C. trinitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Table-UUID="5DE7E2B1F6DB1E28895E50CE44194204" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5DE7E2B1F6DB1E28895E50CE44194204" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" start="Table 4" startId="T4">
